6.9	We recommended that the Management:
Avail of the one-time cleansing of dormant accounts by creating a task force to assist the Municipal Accountant in following the general guidelines and in preparing the required schedules for monitoring purposes as well as undertake the procedures for the proper disposition of dormant accounts as provided for under Items 6.0 and 7.0 of COA Circular 2023-008 dated August 17, 2023;
Direct the Municipal Accountant through the HoA with/through the ATL and/or SA, depending on the jurisdictional amount, to file a request for the approval of COA to write off/derecognize from the books the dormant accounts in compliance with Item 8.0 of the Circular within one (1) year from the effectivity of the Circular. The request shall be supported with the documents listed in Annex 8, provided with index tabs, for easy reference;
Prepare the Schedules of Dormant Accounts (SDA) quarterly to be submitted to the ATL/SA on or before the 15th day of the ensuing month and disclose comparative information in the Notes to Financial Statements relative to the dormant accounts pursuant to Item 10.0 of the Circular; and
Looking forward, ensure that receivables below ten years are properly monitored to ensure their prompt collection and accurate recording in the FS including the provision of an allowance for impairment on receivables with doubtful collectability.

18.10	We therefore recommended the following improvement opportunities to wit:
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to completely and appropriately fill up the RCI, especially on the responsibility center and the nature of the payment portion of the report;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer/authorized personnel in the MTO to stamp “PAID” including the attached official receipts, payroll and liquidation reports and all its supporting documents with date and signature after payment is made to prevent possible re-use of the same on similar transaction, thereby strengthening the internal control system of the Municipality;
Direct all requesting personnel/department to ensure that all the supporting documents such as the Purchase Orders, Requests for Quotation, and Abstract of Bids are completely filled up and signed by all the responsible personnel and that the Disbursement Vouchers are completely signed before payment is made;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that complete supporting documents are attached to the DVs, particularly on the payment of cash advances for wages, etc. and we reiterate that the Municipality make use of past experiences or require confirmation of attendance before finalizing the number of pax to procure in terms of payment for catering services and ensure that all attendees have signed the meal attendance to support the claims, otherwise justify the noted discrepancy as to the meal attendance and number of persons indicated in the Purchase Order;
Prioritized the designation of a functioning GSO to comply with the submission of the required Monthly Report for Official Travels per vehicle and the consolidated Monthly Reports on Fuel Consumption of government vehicles along with its complete supporting attachments in order for the audit team to review the reasonableness of fuel consumed during the period;
Looking forward, direct the Bids and Awards Committee to submit for contract review the payment for goods and services that exceed the threshold for shopping and small value under Annex H of IRR of RA9184;
Immediately submit the 101 canceled checks for CY 2023 for verification;
Submit the noted lacking documents as per attached Annex K as a result of the contract review of the eight (8) Infrastructure projects totaling ₱73,749,799.08; and
Immediately submit the disbursement vouchers and supporting documents of the 78 transaction payments totaling ₱5,072,432.41 (Annex L) to establish the legality of the claims.

We recommended and the Management agreed that:

The Municipal Account provides a valid justification for the non-transfer of the unspent balance for the CY 2018-2020; 

b. The Municipal Accountant and the OIC-Municipal Budget Officer reconcile their records for the CY 2018-2020 LDRRMF as to appropriation, obligation and disbursements and submit relevant transactions documents/ reports for further audit verification; 

c. The Municipal Accountant draw a journal entry voucher to correct the recording of the Trust Liability – DRRM account which had a balance of ₱1,126,852.24 under the General Fund on the transfer of the unexpended balance of CY 2021 QRF and DRRMF – MOOE and the unexpended balance of ₱2,433,160.33 as of December 31, 2022;

d. The Municipal Accountant includes in the disclosure the prior years’ unexpended balances in the Notes to Financial Statements the details on the receipt and utilization of LDRRMF of the Municipality using the required format as required under Item 5.1.16 of COA Circular 2012 -002;

e. The Municipal Accountant makes sure that disclosures made for the unexpended balance for the MDRRMF must be in accordance with Item 5.1.16 of COA Circular 2012 – 002 and the balance must be equal to the Trust Liability – DRRM account in the Financial Statements;

f. Looking forward, the Municipal Accountant maintains a separate registry of Appropriations, Allotments and Obligations (RAAO) for LDRRMF QRF, MOOE and CO to facilitate reconciliation of records with the budget office and maintain Subsidiary ledgers to facilitate the transfers of the agency’s unutilized DRRMF to the special trust fund by year of transfer, receipt of NDRRMF by transferring agency, DRRMF from other LGUs by LGU, and other sources by the donor at the end of each year to present fairly the said accounts in the financial statements at year end.

We recommended to the Management that:

The Municipal Accountant submit a justification and a plan of action on the noted omissions/deficiencies and the non-conduct of one-time cleansing;

The Office of the Mayor immediately assign/designate a GSO to be part of the Inventory Committee in the meantime and appoint a full-pledged GSO to take charge in the recording and safekeeping of the municipality’s properties;

The Inventory Committee, who are temporarily relieved of all regular duties, complete the physical inventory in three (3) months or less and to prepare and submit the approved Physical Inventory Plan to the COA Audit Team at least ten (10) calendar days before the scheduled start of the inventory-taking activities; and

Ensure full implementation of the “One-time cleansing of PPE accounts” as provided for in COA Circular No. 2020-006.

We recommended to the Management that:

The Municipal Accountant submit the Journal Entry Vouchers together with the supporting documents that would warrant the correctness and validity of the adjustments made as well as submit a justification as to the existence of forwarded balances despite prior years’ audit recommendations;

The Municipal Accountant strictly observe honest, accurate, consistent, and transparent recording in its books of accounts by exerting effort on the retrieval of records/reports from respective files that would establish the details of transactions in order to reclassify to its appropriate accounts;

Considering the amount involved, make it a top priority to create a task force who will be relieved from their regular duties to devote their full time in the retrieval of documents and/or hire additional manpower and submit a timetable showing the schedule of activities in retrieving the documents, reconciling reports and adjusting the unreconciled beginning balances to its appropriate accounts for an accurate and reliable financial reporting; and putting into consideration the following:

• In the case of receivables, exhaust all possible means to collect the receivables. Otherwise, request for write-off in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2016-005;

• In the case of payables, exhaust all possible means to pay off the LGU’s accounts. Otherwise, request for write-off in accordance with the provisions of the COA Circular 2016-005;

In the case of fund transfer (due to and due from), coordinate with the partner agencies with whom the funds were transferred and liquidate it.

In view thereof, we recommended that the Management revisit its internal control structure and install an adequate cash management mechanism and controls to improve compliance with the applicable rules and regulations by:

Creating a task force committee composed of particular personnel in the accounting and treasurer’s office in coordination with the Punong Barangays who will strictly follow up and monitor the compliance of the barangays in terms of the following:

• preparation and maintenance of a hardbound/ or compiled cash books of the composite barangays; 
• ensure that all the cashbooks of the AOs are updated and duly certified to determine the correct accountability in any given period;
• timely submission of transaction documents (RCDs, RCRs, DVs, LRs, etc.) of the Barangays to the Accounting Office;
• conduct of quarterly reconciliation between the MTO and MAO for the LGU and between the BT and MAO for the composite barangays; and
• timely and proper bonding of AOs in the Municipality and Barangays.

The Municipal Accountant and the assigned personnel from the accounting office composing the taskforce to proactively and consistently send demand letters to all barangays found to be delayed in the report’s submission, copy furnished this office and ensure that subsidiary ledgers are prepared for the MTO AOs and kept updated for the BT AOs to allow quarterly reconciliation of records;

With strict and proper monitoring of the compliance of barangays, impose disciplinary sanctions to AOs committing the same violations on the rules and regulations and provide rewards/incentives to all those complying AOs; and

Require reporting of accomplishments or feedback mechanisms from the task force created to the LCE or assigned official to keep track of the progress made and challenges encountered in implementing the same.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor strictly observe, enforce and comply with the rules and regulations on the Settlement of Accounts by:

Evaluating the Municipality’s current system or network of methods, procedures and plans to determine the gaps which led to the deficiencies/inefficiencies noted.  After which, install an effective internal control by adopting streamlined processes and procedures to promote efficiency in their processing of DVs and in organizing, submitting and monitoring them, reduce risk or resource loss, increase reliability of management data, enhance accountability and ensure compliance with laws and regulations;

Revisit personnel competence and assignment of duties commensurate with their assigned responsibilities; 

Assign personnel in charge to provide feedback mechanism and monitoring and evaluation of the accounts and operations of the Municipality to the Municipal Mayor; and

Initiate the necessary disciplinary, administrative and/or criminal action in case of unjustified failure/refusal to effect compliance with the requirements by subordinate officials who are the subject of repeated adverse audit findings as the evidence may warrant.

We recommended that the Management:

Strengthen the internal controls in the petty cash management system of the LGU to ensure that the operations are effective and efficient, assets are safeguarded, financial reports are complete and accurate and the Agency is compliant with the laws, rules and regulations. 

Improve the procurement planning especially on the supplies needed in the MDRRMO, JCI and JILLT and revisit the necessity of setting up the five (5) Petty Cash Fund to avoid using the fund to pay for personal, regular and recurring expenses; 

Direct the Municipal Treasurer or his authorized staff that liquidation reports and other documents attached especially the official receipts shall be stamped “paid” with date and signature of the MT to preclude re-use;

Enhance compliance with the laws, rules and regulations by maintaining the petty cash fund under the imprest system and follow the proper procedure in the treatment of petty cash fund in accordance with Section 48 of the NGAS for LGUs and the Revised Chart of Accounts to properly classify the account in the year-end Financial Statement;

Require the Petty Cash Custodian to liquidate the fund at year-end, return the unused cash and effect proper cut-off in its cashbook;

Submit additional supporting documents to support the validity and legality of the claims made against the Petty Cash Fund particularly on the payment of meals and snacks, catering, registration fee for the ANC, sponsorship and solicitation, lechon, fuel and repairs and payment for auto and spare parts; and

Henceforth, comply with the provisions of Section 4 of PD 1445 and COA Circular No. 2012-001 as to the documentary requirements for its disbursements, in order to establish the validity and legality of the claims to the fund.

We recommended and Management agreed to:

Stop the practice of granting cash advances and petty cash replenishments for the payment of regular operating expenses;

Conduct a detailed planning of the Municipality’s activities and conduct of operations to completely eradicate the need to issue cash advances for regular operations;

Provide each department head and elected officials a copy of COA Circular No. 97-002 to remind them of the allowable cash advances that may be granted along with a refresher on the proper time to liquidate once a CA’s purpose is served;

Establish an efficient internal control on the usage and recording of petty cash fund; and

Practice the withholding of taxes on all government purchases;

We recommended that Management:

Immediately designate a General Service Officer available to handle the procurement and maintenance of supplies, including the monitoring and reporting of its issuance to enhance the LGU’s compliance with the guidelines on procurement;

Prepare and submit the Annual Procurement Plan – Common Use Supplies and Equipment (APP-CSE) for 2024 to the Procurement Service of the Department of Budget and Management (PS-DBM) via the Virtual Store (VS) within the prescribed period this year;

Require each department/ end-user unit to carefully plan and monitor the procurement of common use supplies through proper forecasting, projections, and estimations of inventories to be used and stocked and accomplish the PPMP template before submitting the same to the Budget Officer for Budget approval and BAC Secretariat for consolidation;

Direct the Designated General Service Officer to coordinate with the BAC secretariat to get the consolidated and funded APP in order to make a detailed and thorough three-month forecast of the common-use supplies to be purchased by the Municipality in the PS-DBM; 

After which procure the unavailable items from the PS-DBM comprising the three-month supplies from other suppliers using the RFQ in order to avail of advantageous bulk purchase prices and also to avoid price fluctuations of purchasing the same supplies from different suppliers; and

Monitor the issuance of supplies to each department by using the Requisition Issue Slip and reporting the same to the Accounting Department monthly using the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued for the month together with the stock card as proof.

We recommended that the Management:

Observe practicality in the disbursement of public funds and:

Minimize spending traveling expenses. Instead, conduct meetings and planning conferences in the local vicinities as much as practicable; 

Revisit the provisions of EO 77 by claiming only the correct amount of travel allowance; if accommodations, meals, and transportation are provided by third parties or already shouldered by the LGU, stop the practice of claiming its corresponding value in the daily travel allowance;

Revisit the guidelines of CSC Memorandum Circular No.6, series of 2002 when granting loyalty awards to ensure that awardees have successfully passed its criteria of the ten-year continuous and satisfactory government service;

Judicious use on the grant, expenditure and usage of the petty cash funds; remind the Accountable Officers that government funds are to be used to further the government’s operations;

Penalties incurred in the settlement of utilities, bills, and mandatory deductions should be borne by the person(s) who caused the delay; 

Recheck the LGU’s 21 PLDT accounts if it is possible for two offices to share one account. If possible, cancel the redundant accounts. Provide a justification as to why the Municipal Mayor was granted three postpaid plan accounts. Otherwise, discontinue the two needless plans as its presence signify an unnecessary expenditure;

Make use of past experiences or require confirmation of attendance before finalizing the number of pax to procure in terms of payment for catering services and ensure that all attendees have signed the meal attendance to support the claims;

Looking forward, direct the Local Finance Committee to manage and observe prudence in the disbursement of funds, institute austerity measures to prioritize expenditures and undertake revenue enhancing strategies and generate cash savings to fund more important projects/ activities of the LGU.

